trajectory:
The expected value of playing the game is the sum of the probability of winning and losing multiplied by the respective amount.  In this case, the probability of winning is the probability of drawing a white ball, which is $\frac{3}{3+k}$, and the probability of losing is the probability of drawing a black ball, which is $\frac{k}{3+k}$.  Therefore, the expected value is
\begin{align*}
E&=\left(\frac{3}{3+k}\right)(1)+\left(\frac{k}{3+k}\right)(-1)\\
&=\frac{3}{3+k}-\frac{k}{3+k}\\
&=\frac{3-k}{3+k}
\end{align*}
Since we are given that the expected loss is 50 cents, which is $-\frac{1}{2}$ dollars, we have
\begin{align*}
-\frac{1}{2}&=\frac{3-k}{3+k}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad-1&=3-k+k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad-1&=3\\
\end{align*}
This is not true.  We made an error in our previous steps.  We can correct this by multiplying both sides of the equation by $(3+k)$ to get
\begin{align*}
-\frac{1}{2}(3+k)&=(3-k)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -\frac{3}{2}-\frac{k}{2}&=3-k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -\frac{k}{2}+k&=3+\frac{3}{2}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{2k}{2}&=\frac{9}{2}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\frac{9}{2}
\end{align*}
This is not a positive integer, so we made another error.  We can correct this by multiplying both sides of the equation by $2$ to get
\begin{align*}
-(3+k)&=2(3-k)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -3-k&=6-2k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -3-6&=2k-k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -9&=k
\end{align*}
This is not a positive integer, so we made another error.  We can correct this by multiplying both sides of the equation by $-1$ to get
\begin{align*}
3+k&=-2(3-k)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3+k&=-6+2k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3+6&=2k-k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 9&=k
\end{align*}
Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{9}$.

