To find the distance from the center point $P$ of one square base to the corner $Q$ of the opposite base, we need to first find the length of the diagonal of the square base and then find the length of the space diagonal of the rectangular box.

The length of the diagonal of the square base can be found using the Pythagorean theorem. Since the square base measures $168776$ cm by $168776$ cm, we have:

\begin{align*}
d^2&=a^2+b^2\\
&=(168776)^2+(168776)^2\\
&=2(168776)^2\\
&=2\cdot 2.85\times 10^{8}\\
&=5.7\times 10^{8}
\end{align*}

So the length of the diagonal of the square base is $\sqrt{5.7\times 10^{8}}$ cm.

The length of the space diagonal of the rectangular box can be found using the three-dimensional version of the Pythagorean theorem:

\begin{align*}
d^2&=a^2+b^2+c^2\\
&=(168776)^2+(168776)^2+(312768)^2\\
&=2(168776)^2+(312768)^2\\
&=2\cdot 2.85\times 10^{8}+9.76\times 10^{8}\\
&=1.57\times 10^{9}
\end{align*}

So the length of the space diagonal of the rectangular box is $\sqrt{1.57\times 10^{9}}$ cm.

However, we want to find the distance from the center point $P$ of one square base to the corner $Q$ of the opposite base. This distance is the hypotenuse of a right triangle with legs equal to half the length of the diagonal of the square base and the height of the box. Therefore, we can find this distance by using the Pythagorean theorem again:

\begin{align*}
