trajectory:
We have that $\angle AOC = 2 \cdot 1^\circ = 2^\circ.$ Since $AC = BC,$ then $\angle BAC = \angle BCA.$  We know that the sum of the interior angles of a triangle is $180^\circ.$  Thus, we have that \begin{align*}
\angle BAC + \angle BCA + \angle ABC &= 180^\circ\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 2 \cdot \angle BAC + \angle BAC + 90^\circ &= 180^\circ\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3 \cdot \angle BAC &= 90^\circ\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \angle BAC &= 30^\circ
\end{align*} Now, we note that $\triangle AOB$ is an isosceles triangle, and we have that $\angle BAO = \angle BCO = 1^\circ.$  Therefore, \begin{align*}
\angle AOB &= 180^\circ - 2 \cdot \angle BAO\\
&= 180^\circ - 2 \cdot 1^\circ\\
&= \boxed{178^\circ}
\end{align*}

